caption: Food was decent recommend the sliders and toasted cheese.  Service a little rushed even when not busy...

Interesting theme, but the food tried a little hard to be relevant.
Very nostalgic and the food is good. Going to have to go back soon.
Nastalgia was great! The mac and cheese was the best.
I never expected that the food would be so amazing! The Mac & Cheese, Sliders, and everything else is delicious. So grateful to go to the Max after all those years of watching it on TV!
Diner food, extra nostalgia.

Windy City Blogger Collective recently held a dinner at the Saved By The Max. The atmosphere is fun and really plays off the 90s vibes. All the bloggers were blown away by the quality of the food. They did a great job of creating menu items that took diner food to the next level.
The attention to detail in terms of decor were great.  But the food was mediocre at best, and the service was sub-meh.
The ambiance is what makes the place. Everything is overpriced but is a must see for a Saved by the Bell fan.
Fun place with decent food
Huge fan of Saved By the Bell and this place does my Nerdy-ness Justice!
Lots of fun. Really well done decor to mimic the Saved by the Bell series from the early 90s. The food is above average quality, but not amazing. Worth coming here with other fans of the show.
The decor was spot on and super fun, but the food was blah. Not worth the price
Great experience,  wish it was a permanent location. Great food and service, friendly staff. Don't miss it, experience it while you can.

Fun place with great food.  Just a diner dressed up as Max's from Saved by the Bell.  Fried chicken was excellent and for a short menu it was a good one including the drink choices.  It's bright and casual.  It's busy though so come early.
It's a themed pop-up so reviews probably won't stop you from visiting if you plan to already. Go there for drinks and appetizers but anything more is a wasted. Food is poor and service is ok at best
Place sucks!!!!! Bring it to California where it belongs....over hyped don't go
Great pop up restaurant! The food was surprisingly good and inexpensive.
This place brings back all the memories. The food is higher quality diner. I loved the A.C.Sliders, roasted Brussels Sprouts, grilled cheese with sautéed mushrooms.
Absolutely loved it, atmosphere, employees, everything is great tasting and spot on

The food is good but you won't come here for it. Leave plenty of time for pictures to be taken of you with the Zack Morris phone prop, character head cutouts and trips to the payphone by the door. Immersive experience, friendly staff great times, at the the Max.

Very fun place, food was terrible though

The wait is extremely long and when you get in you're extremely disappointed. The food and drinks are ok and the service is meh.There's Saved by the Bell decor, but not as much nor as clever as one would hope.

Very nostalgic. Fans of Saved By The Bell will really enjoy it. They recreated The Max just as it was on the television show. They also have things around the restaurant with nuggets from the show that will bring back memories. The staff was very friendly and the food was pretty good and filling.
Only bad thing is that is is temporary
Fun times. Lots of food. Typical diner food. Boozie milkshake is awesome.

This place was booked for months out. You can stand in line and wait forever if you're really adamant about trying it, but then you get stuck at an awful side table where they store the giant head cutouts of all the characters so you've got customers coming by you and grabbing them for pictures the entire time you're there. The food was absolutely awful and I ended up getting sick the same night and vomiting. The inside looked very similar to the show except 1/10th the size. Pretty much it would have been much more satisfying had I just checked the inside out for a couple minutes and then left. Definitely not worth the aggravation I went through to try it.
Great decor, food was so so... The draw is def the ambience
very friendly and lively. great time

Saved By The Bell was one of my favorite childhood shows. To visit The Max in real life was quite a treat. I'm glad they ended the pop up until December. This allowed my friends and I the opportunity to visit. Walks-ins are welcomed, and I recommend arriving before they open to get in line for a chance to dine. Service was great as was the atmosphere.

They definitely get five stars for the fun and kitch factor. The food for me was a bit hit or miss. I had the five spice chicken wings for my app and they were really good. I would definitely get them again. My friend had the brocollini and that was actually the best thing I ate!  For entrees, I ordered the Monte Cristo and it was good but didn't blow me away. It had a grainy mustard on it; which is something I'm not used to and while I didn't hate it, I also thought it overpowered the other flavors in the sandwich. My friend had the fried chicken and that was really good. It was extremely spicy; which I liked, but she didn't and she was surprised by it.  Dessert for me was lacking sadly. Maybe we ordered the wrong thing. I had the candied bacon and even though it was super delicious bacon, I guess I was expecting it to be something else. I've had brown sugar bacon, chocolate bacon and bacon brittle before so that's what I was anticipating. What I got was very good bacon with some carmely, sugared edges. Still good. My friend had the blueberry ice cream with the cone in it. Very good, but nothing out of this world.  This was my second time there and the first time I was really impressed by how good the drinks tasted. This time, the drinks were really really strong so that was impressive, but they were so strong all I tasted was alcohol. I know, seriously, I'm not complaining, just pointing out a fact.  Let's face it - I'd for sure come back. It's The Max!!! Late night is good enough for me though. I can skip the food next time. Glad I had a chance to try it.

The experience is pretty good. The servers, bartenders, hostesses are a little annoyed at this point and don't care that you're super into it. The food is below par. I won't say bad because I've had worse but the food is really just okay, maybe that. Get some pictures and maybe the $92 is worth it.
Cool fun little pop up spot that brings you back to your childhood. Food was above average and the service was fantastic.

The moment you walk into Saved By The Max you are transported back to the 90s and it couldn't be any cooler.  The job they did trying to model it after the Max from Saved by the Bell is great! We got a the table next to the door that Zach Morris would have walked through.  They have a themed cocktail menu with classic favorites with a few twists. Nothing crazy. The old fashioned was pretty good.  As part of the reservation we got an appetizer, an entree, and a dessert. My girlfriend and I shared the AC Sliders and the Mac and Screech for our appetizers. The mac and cheese was ok but the AC Sliders were the real winner.  For the main course we shared the Bayside Burger and the Kelly Kewpowski which is a monte cristo. Both were very good. You get to choose a side and we had a biscuit from Bang Bang Pie which I know is an odd side but it was a killer biscuit.  For dessert we shared the candied bacon and the pie slice of the day from Bang Bang Pie which was a salted chocolate caramel. It was a wonderful combination.  I wouldn't say the food is next level but it's a nice approximation of what I think the kids would have had at the Max but then modernized. The real winner with Saved by the Max is the experience. Not to be missed!

The pop-up idea is great, though overall the experience is a bit confusing as there is not a lot of information online. Getting reservations for dinner is almost impossible, however, if you watch random times will appear on their site at random. They are open late (2 AM except for Sundays), and we were able to get seated in about 10 mins as a walk in around 1130PM on a Friday. After being seated though we were told that we get not order food, only drinks. I tried to get a milkshake as well and was denied saying it had to be drinks (Though that was odd as a couple tables around us were being served ice cream). The novelty wore off in about 5 minutes.
Closed at least 45 minutes before their scheduled close time which is posted on the door and on this site.

Doesn't matter what you order, it will be amazing. Finally had my dinner reservation Saturday, Aug 27th, and all my high expectations were exceeded. In addition to the near perfect recreation of the screen-used set (which makes up the bulk of the restaurant), a generous bar with three screens running episodes of Saved by the Bell, and additional niche seating areas recreating Mr. Belding's office or Miss Bliss's classroom make for a nostalgia thrill ride wherever you look.  As for the food, unless you food allergies or specific dietary restrictions, don't bother reading the full descriptions, just pick a title that sounds amusing or fun and enjoy. Every dish will be exquisite, and surpass expectations. As an example, my entree included a side of "Mr. Belding's French Fries". One does not ttpically expect much from french fries, yet these were seasoned beautifully and perfectly cooked with not a burnt end in the bunch. In more complicated dishes the chef truly shines as the sauces (whether for the biscuits and gravy, or enhancng the pulled pork of the AC Sliders) both delight and amaze.  In short, I could not be more excited about this restauarant and sincerely hope to secure another reaervation before their closing (currently planned for New Year's). Even if this became a permanently open restauarant, you would likely always need a reservation - both due to the limited seating, and the exquisite food that is sure to stay in high demand.
You really feel like you are in the Saved By the Bell studio when you go here.  Really brings me back to when I was a teen. The staff was super friendly and the food was pretty good.
Cool but very busy!

Wow😀 my mind is blown. The food was impeccable, the decor was true to the original set, staff was very knowledgeable and to top it off they played the show on several televisions. It's a MUST SEE! Even if you can't get a reservation go am hour or two early and you'll get in.
A great blast from the past! I honestly felt like I was in Saved by the Bell for a minute!  The food was also pretty darn good! I was quite impressed!  The service was also fantastic!

Great experience! Food was delicious and definitely want to go back.

This pop up restaurant is open through December 2016 and if you love Saved by the Bell you have to eat here before they're gone! I didn't have a reservation but arrived 20 min before opening and a line had already formed. Though the wait was about an hour it was worth it. There are tables and a lunch counter where you can sit and watch SBTB. While I was waiting for my meal a staff member started conversation with me, took pictures in the restaurant for me, and gave me SBTB trading cards. The food was great and reasonably priced. I will certainly try to go back before December!

They had a Zak Attack band that didn't sound great and they stopper serving food at 11. It's very small inside

THIS IS SO MUCH FUN.  My boyfriend surprised me with tickets as an early anniversary surprise - aptly timed so we can swing through Chicago on our way home to Milwaukee from vacation. I was seriously excited and not at all disappointed, given my high expectations. Let me break it down for you.  The process: Yes, it's sold out. They MIGHT be able to get you in from the walk-in line, but don't count on it. When we arrived, staff came out to get our name, and those with reservations were called in and seated. We saw a few people from the line outside get seated at a table, but not many. It's a crap-shoot, but honestly, I'd try for it if I were you (see below). Because it's a FREAKING BLAST.  The atmosphere: So perfect, down to the last detail. Mr. Belding's Office, the jukebox, the payphone, the lockers, the music, the servers, the booths and tables...you feel like you're in the 90's again hanging with Kelly & Zack and the crew. If you loved SBTB at all, you're love it. If you're like me and REALLY loved SBTB, and still do...you can't miss this. The staff were upbeat and accommodating and offered to take tons of pics for us.  The food: Exceeded expectations! There's a good chef here, and it shows. Our favorite app was the Mac n' Screech (decadent, delicious), and we sampled the Kelly Kapowski and Tori's Fried Chicken for entrees and were pleasantly surprised by the flavor and uniqueness of both. The chicken has a KICK to it, and it was so interesting and yummy. We both got the Snack Attack for dessert (Twinkie ice cream, strawberry accent) and the flavor was so amazing it made we want to get up and do "the Sprain." One of the best restaurant desserts I've had in a long time.  Can't forget, THE DRINKS: The cocktails have great names that only a true fan could love. I got the "I'm So Excited" and found it to be the perfect blend of sweet and tart. Could have sipped those for days. My boyfriend enjoyed the "Last Dance," which was also delicious and summery. (On that note, what was with Kelly and Jeff? Seriously, girl, never date your boss, and you know you and Zack were meant to be so just realize it and move on.)  In summary, we left full, happy, a bit giddy from the nostalgia, and feeling like we definitely got our money's worth. It might be hard to get in, but it's worth it. Did Screech give up on asking out Lisa after he got denied the first time? Nope. (So neither should you, with Saved by the Max.)  GO BAYSIDE.
